{
  "text": "Resveratrol (3, 4\u2032, 5-trihydroxystilbene, RSV) is a polyphenolic compound found mainly in the skins of grapes, and berry fruits (cranberry, strawberry, mulberry, etc.), and in peanuts and red wine. Accumulating evidence suggests that RSV is a highly pleiotropic molecule that modulates abundant targets and thus influences numerous biochemical and molecular functions. [CITATION_1] Epidemiological studies indicate that the Mediterranean diet, which is rich in RSV, is associated with a reduced risk of carotid AS. [CITATION_2] Evidence from clinical trials indicated that RSV may protect against AS by improving gene expression in the vascular endothelium, and could be considered as a preventive agent. [CITATION_3] We previously found that RSV could penetrate into vascular endothelial cells and attenuate endothelial inflammation by inducing autophagy through the cyclic adenosine monophosphate (cAMP) signaling pathway. [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] Nonetheless, little information is available regarding the effects of RSV on mtROS homeostasis regulation in endothelial cells.",
